abstract.gco:CharacterString: This polygon data layer represents land use for Rock County, Wisconsin in 2010. It is a feature class within the geodatabase 'Rock_LandUse_2010.gdb'. [The Rock County Land Use Inventory was designed using a Classification System designed by Planning Staff to be able to capture land use traits important in staff decisions. The main purpose of the inventory is to is to descrive what actually takes place in physical or observable terms. The land use classification definitions and a look up table are attached to the metadata as enclosures. To access them, in ArcCatalog click on the metadata properties button on the metadata toolbar.Please note:The classification system in this Inventory is NOT COMPATIBLE with the APA LBCS that was used in the 2000 Land Use Inventory. Users SHOULD NOT use the numerical codes as a basis of analysis between the two data sets.]

purpose.gco:CharacterString:
This layer is intended for reference and mapping purposes, and may be used for basic applications such as viewing, querying, and map output production, or to provide a basemap to support graphical overlays and analysis with other spatial data.
[The Land Use Inventory is intended to be used within the Rock County Geographic Information System as a dynamic inventory of land uses within the county. Unlike previous inventories it is the intent of the department to update the land uses as they occur or are discovered.]

supplementalInformation.gco:CharacterString:
Augmented original metadata with UW-Madison specific elements.
[The basic unit of analysis was the tax parcel. Orthophotos and Pictometery images were used to analyze the land use that could be identified from the observation of the parcel (e.g. cropland, cemeteries, etc.). When the identity of land use could not be obtained using orthophotos and Pictometry provided by Rock County, imagery from Bing and Google maps were used for a second and third observational source. If the land use could not be identified through observation of photogrammetry, a combination of select feature classes were used to help identify the land use. A Google search of the address was conducted for identifying the land use classification in addition to the combined previous methods if the land use was still in question. For any land use that could not be identified by a combination of any of the previous methods a windshield survey was conducted to identify the land use.]

description.gco:CharacterString: Exported original feature class into a new file geodatabase to maintain the original file format of the data and to conform to UW-Madison's data distribution plan.
